<p>Boris Johnson has accused the European Union of demanding an &ldquo;extortionate&rdquo; amount of money in the Brexit negotiations and said the United Kingdom will not pay.</p><br />
<p>It has been reported that Brussels <a href="https://www.ft.com/content/cc7eed42-2f49-11e7-9555-23ef563ecf9a?mhq5j=e2" target="_blank">could ask for &euro;60bn, or as much as &euro;100bn</a>, from Britain as the price for leaving the EU.</p><br />
<p>The price tag is based on financial obligations the other member states believe the UK would need to settle on its way out the door.</p><br />
<p>Speaking in the Commons today, Johnson said: &ldquo;The sums that I have seen they propose to demand from this country seem to me to be extortionate.&rdquo;</p><br />
<p>The foreign secretary agreed with eurosceptic Tory backbencher Philip Hollobone who said Brussels should not expect the UK to pay any more money than it already has.</p><br />
<p>Hollobone asked Johnson: &ldquo;Will you make it clear to the EU that if they want a penny piece more then they can go whistle?&rdquo;</p><br />
<p>Johnson&rsquo;s comments appear at odds with Brexit secretary David Davis, who has said the UK will &ldquo;meet&rdquo; its &ldquo;legal&rdquo;&nbsp;obligations.</p><br />
<p>The foreign secretary also said there was &ldquo;no plan&rdquo; for what would happen if the UK failed to agree a Brexit deal with the EU.</p><br />
<p>&ldquo;There is no plan for no deal because we are going to get a great deal,&rdquo; he said.</p><br />
<p>But James Chapman, a former senior adviser Davis, said it &ldquo;<a href="https://twitter.com/jameschappers/status/884741468656730112" target="_blank">factually incorrect</a>&rdquo; to say no planning had been done.</p><br />
<p>Emily Thornberry, the shadow foreign secretary, criticised the government for failing to produce a contingency plan.</p><br />
<p>&ldquo;It is the prime minister,&nbsp;at least the prime minister for now, who decided to put the idea of the &lsquo;no deal&rsquo; option on the table - and she couldn&rsquo;t stop using the phrase during the election,&rdquo; she told MPs.</p><br />
<p>Thornberry asked Johnson: &ldquo;What would no deal would mean? Can he reassure us, if he is not prepared to tell us publicly, at the very least he has a detailed private plan to manage that risk.&rdquo;</p><br />
<p>Tom Brake, the Lib Dem Brexit spokesman, said the lack of a plan for no deal showed a &ldquo;shocking level of complacency&rdquo;.</p><br />
<p>&ldquo;These kind of glib assurances are straight out of the Trump playbook. It is simply not good enough when people&rsquo;s jobs, living standards and rights are all on the line,&rdquo; he said.</p><br />
<p>&ldquo;People should be able to judge Boris Johnson on his actions not his words, with the chance to reject a disastrous Brexit deal and stay in the EU.&rdquo;</p><br />
<p>&nbsp;Yesterday Australian prime minister Malcolm Turnbull has said his country wants to seal a free trade agreement with the UK &ldquo;as soon as possible&rdquo; after Britain&rsquo;s withdrawal from the EU.</p><br />
<p>Turnbull&rsquo;s comments came after he held talks at 10 Downing Street with Theresa May, who revealed that International Trade Secretary Liam Fox will visit Australia in the &ldquo;coming months&rdquo; as part of ongoing talks on an agreement.</p><br />
